Leetcode boilerplate.description:
[Boilerplate] LeetCode-style template. Includes bits/stdc++.h, mt19937_64 RNG seeded from system clock, and a main() with high-resolution nanosecond timer (printed to stderr). Conditional debug header included via #ifndef ONLINE_JUDGE. Use $1 for helper functions/structs, $0 for main logic.
Usage:
  // $1 = helper structs/functions area
  // $0 = main logic cursor
  // RNG, timer, debug guard included automatically

Boilerplate debugged.description:
[Boilerplate] Full competitive-programming template with debug support. Features: #define int long long, pii, endl='\n', mt19937_64 RNG, fast I/O (sync_with_stdio+cin.tie), file redirection (_in.txt/_out.txt) under ONLINE_JUDGE guard, multi-test-case loop via solve(). Millisecond timer printed to stderr. $1 to toggle test-case input, $0 inside solve().
Usage:
  // $0 inside solve(); $1 toggles 'cin >> testCases'
  // Locally: reads _in.txt, writes _out.txt
  // On judge: #ifdef guard disables file I/O and debug

Boilerplate with debugging.description:
[Boilerplate] Competitive-programming template without file I/O redirection. Same as 'dboi' (int=ll, pii, RNG, fast I/O, multi-testcase loop, ms timer) but reads stdin/stdout directly — safe to submit as-is. $1 to toggle test-case read, $0 inside solve().
Usage:
  // $0 inside solve(); $1 toggles test-case read
  // stdout/stdin direct; safe to submit as-is

Rolling hash simpler.description:
[String Hashing] Simple polynomial rolling hash over a string. Base=911, uses unsigned long long (natural mod 2^64). Functions: precalc() — precomputes power array p[]; build(s) — fills prefix hash array ha[]; get_hash(l,r) — O(1) hash of substring s[l..r]; pattern_hash(s) — hash of a short pattern string. Collision chance ~1/2^64; fast but no explicit modulus guard. O(N) build, O(1) query.
Usage:
  precalc();
  build(s);
  ull h  = get_hash(l, r);    // hash of s[l..r]
  ull ph = pattern_hash(pat); // hash of pattern string

vectors.description:
[Utility] Declares a vector<int> with the given name. Quick shorthand — type 'vi' then name. $1=name, $0=next cursor.
Usage:
  vi arr;  // expands to: vector<int> arr;

vector<vector>.description:
[Utility] Declares a 2D vector<vector<int>> with given name and dimensions. $1=name, $2=rows, $3=cols, $0=next cursor.
Usage:
  vvi g 3 4;  // expands to: vector<vector<int>> g(3, vector<int>(4));

Trie.description:
[Data Structure] Standard Trie for lowercase English strings (26 children). Methods: insert(key) — O(|key|); search(key) — exact match, O(|key|), returns bool; starts_with(pref) — prefix existence check, O(|pref|), returns bool. Each TrieNode holds child[26] pointers and an is_end flag. Memory: O(total chars * 26).
Usage:
  Trie t;
  t.insert("apple");
  t.search("apple");       // true
  t.starts_with("app");   // true

Singly Linked List Node.description:
[Data Structure] Singly linked list node struct (LeetCode-style). Fields: val (int), next (ListNode*). Constructor sets val and next=NULL. Use as building block for linked-list problems.
Usage:
  ListNode* head = new ListNode(1);
  head->next = new ListNode(2);

Binary Tree Node.description:
[Data Structure] Binary tree node struct (LeetCode-style). Fields: val (int), left/right (TreeNode*). Constructor sets val and both children to NULL. Standard base for tree traversal problems.
Usage:
  TreeNode* root = new TreeNode(1);
  root->left  = new TreeNode(2);
  root->right = new TreeNode(3);

ordered_set.description:
[Data Structure] Policy-based ordered_set from GCC PBDS (pb_ds). Backed by red-black tree. Like std::set but adds: order_of_key(x) — number of elements < x, O(log N); find_by_order(k) — iterator to k-th element (0-indexed), O(log N). Use with #include <ext/pb_ds/...>. Template alias: ordered_set<T>.
Usage:
  ordered_set<int> s;
  s.insert(3);
  s.order_of_key(3);    // # of elements strictly < 3
  *s.find_by_order(0);  // 0-th smallest element

Custom Hash Struct.description:
[Utility] Anti-hack custom hash for unordered_map/set using splitmix64 mixer. Avoids worst-case O(N) collisions from adversarial inputs. The FIXED_RANDOM salt is seeded from system clock at runtime. Based on http://xorshift.di.unimi.it/splitmix64.c.
Usage:
  unordered_map<ll, int, custom_hash> mp;
  unordered_set<ll, custom_hash> st;

Dijkstra Lambda Alt.description:
[Graph] Dijkstra's SSSP as a capture-by-reference lambda. Requires: adj (adjacency list of {neighbor,weight} pairs), spath (dist vector pre-filled with INF, except spath[src]=0). Uses min-heap (priority_queue with greater<>). Time O((V+E) log V). Skips stale entries via the spath[curr_node] < curr_dis guard.
Usage:
  // adj: vector<vector<pair<int,int>>> adj(n)
  vector<int> dist(n, INF); dist[src] = 0;
  dj(src, dist); // fills dist[] with shortest paths

Rabin-Karp Rolling Hash.description:
[String Hashing] Rabin-Karp class with polynomial rolling hash (BASE=256, MOD=1e9+7). Methods: RabinKarp(maxLen) — precomputes powers; computeHash(s) — O(|s|) full hash; updateHash(oldHash, oldChar, newChar, patLen) — O(1) sliding-window hash update. Best used for multi-pattern matching. Beware single-mod collisions on adversarial input.
Usage:
  RabinKarp rk(maxLen);
  ll ph = rk.computeHash(pattern);
  ll th = rk.computeHash(text.substr(0, m));
  th = rk.updateHash(th, text[i], text[i+m], m); // slide window

rolling_hash.description:
[String Hashing] High-quality polynomial rolling hash using __int128 arithmetic (base=33, prime mod=1e18+3). Collision-resistant for competitive programming. Functions: precalc() — O(N) power & inverse-power tables; build(s) — O(N) prefix hash; getHash(x,y) — O(1) normalized hash of s[x..y] (position-independent, comparable across substrings). Use to compare substrings in O(1) after O(N) build.
Usage:
  precalc();
  build(s);
  __int128 h = getHash(l, r);             // normalized hash of s[l..r]
  if (getHash(l1,r1) == getHash(l2,r2))  // compare substrings

bellman_ford.description:
[Graph] Bellman-Ford SSSP as a lambda (capture by ref). Runs N-1 relaxation passes over all edges (edge struct with .a, .b, .x fields). Then a second N-1 pass detects negative cycles by setting reachable nodes to -inf. Requires: edges[], dist[] (pre-filled with inf/−inf sentinels), n (node count). Time O(V*E).
Usage:
  // set dist[src]=0, all others=INF
  bellman_ford();
  // dist[v] == -INF -> v on or reachable from a negative cycle

Topological Sort.description:
[Graph] Kahn's BFS-based topological sort (class). Takes adjacency list by reference. Constructor computes in-degrees and runs BFS. Methods: getTopo() — returns topological order vector (empty or partial if graph has a cycle); isDAG() — returns true iff no cycle detected (sorted count == n). Time O(V+E).
Usage:
  Topology tp(adj);
  if (tp.isDAG()) {
    auto order = tp.getTopo(); // valid topological ordering
  }

generate submasks.description:
[Bitmask] Enumerates all submasks of a given bitmask in O(2^popcount(mask)). The loop 'for(sub=mask;;sub=(sub-1)&mask)' visits every subset of set bits, ending at sub=0. Prints each submask as a 4-bit binary string (adjust bitset size). Commonly used in bitmask DP over subsets.
Usage:
  genSubmasks(0b1011);
  // visits: 1011, 1010, 1001, 1000, 0011, 0010, 0001, 0000

sum over subsets.description:
[Bitmask DP] Sum Over Subsets (SOS) DP. Given array A of values, builds F[] where F[mask] = count of elements in A that are submasks of mask. Runs in O(N * 2^N). Standard technique for subset-sum convolution and bitmask DP optimizations. Returns F after transformation.
Usage:
  auto F = SOS(N, A);
  // F[mask] = # of A[i] values that are submasks of mask

function to measure time.description:
[Utility] Wraps any callable in a nanosecond-precision timer. measure_time(name, func) — runs func(), measures wall-clock duration via chrono::high_resolution_clock, prints 'name: X ms' to stderr. Output goes to stderr so it doesn't interfere with stdout answers.
Usage:
  measure_time("solve", [&]() { solve(); });
  // stderr: "solve: 12.34 ms"

Trie-with-Aho-Corasik.description:
[String] Aho-Corasick automaton built on a Trie. Supports multi-pattern matching. Methods: insert(s, id) — add pattern string s with integer id; build() — constructs BFS-based failure links (like KMP's LPS but on a Trie), also propagates output links so every node's out[] contains all matching pattern ids. After build(), traverse text char-by-char and check node->out. Time: O(total pattern length) build + O(text length + matches) search.
Usage:
  TrieAC ac;
  ac.insert("he", 0); ac.insert("she", 1);
  ac.build();
  // traverse text: follow child links, check node->out for matched ids
